## Transitions

<!-- awf:section transitions -->
- `Proposed → Accepted` lands in the commit that finalises the design.
- `Accepted → Implemented` lands in the final commit of the implementation sequence.
- `Proposed → Implemented` directly (skipping `Accepted`) is allowed when design and implementation land together in a single commit.
- Any live state → `Superseded` is an in-place status edit made when *coverage completes*: every Decision item and every declared invariant slug carries a retirement token from an `Implemented` ADR. The flip lands in the commit that brings the final covering ADR to `Implemented`, which is usually not the commit that created it. `awf check` derives coverage and refuses drift in both directions.
<!-- awf:end -->

## Supersedence flavours

<!-- awf:section supersedence-full -->
### Full supersedence

The successor replaces the predecessor wholesale. Apply when most of the predecessor is mechanically obsolete.

- Predecessor frontmatter: `status: Superseded`, bare and naming no successor (in-place edit; on a non-Proposed ADR only `status` and cross-reference metadata may be edited). It names none because coverage may split across several successors, so a scalar would lie; the claimants are recoverable from the predecessor's `related:` back-pointers.
- `{{ .layout.activeMd }}` records the chain in its "Supersedence chains" section (auto-generated; never hand-edit).
- An ADR may have several successors: full supersedence is the emergent case of every anchor being retired, and different successors may retire different anchors. `awf check` enforces that the derived coverage and the hand-written status agree.
- Full supersession excludes partial tokens from the same successor into the same target; `awf check` refuses the mixed pair.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section supersedence-partial -->
### Partial-item supersedence

The successor overrides specific Decision items or Invariants of the predecessor without replacing it as a whole. Apply when most of the predecessor still holds and only one decision needs revisiting.

- Successor frontmatter: `related: [predecessor-number]` (NOT `supersedes:`).
- Predecessor frontmatter: add the successor's number to `related:`, in the **same commit**. Without this back-pointer the overridden Decision item reads as current guidance and a reader of the predecessor gets no signal it was overridden. This is a metadata-only edit, allowed on a live ADR; the body stays append-only.
- Predecessor's `status` field is **NOT** flipped; it stays `Accepted`/`Implemented`.
- The successor's Decision section carries `` `supersedes: ADR-NNNN#<item>` `` (a Decision item) or `` `supersedes-invariant: ADR-NNNN#<slug>` `` (an invariant) as an inline code token at the citation site, **one token per overridden anchor**. Use `` `refines: ADR-NNNN#<item>` `` instead when the successor *adapts* an item rather than replacing it: a refinement counts toward nothing, so an ADR whose items have only been refined stays live. Slug anchors have no refinement form - a slug is atomic. Use `` `cites: ADR-NNNN#<item>` `` or `` `cites-invariant: ADR-NNNN#<slug>` `` when the item *mentions* another ADR's anchor without changing it: a citation asserts nothing, counts toward nothing, and renders nowhere. It exists because a citation check reports an override verb sitting in a Decision item beside an anchor citation that carries no token, and an author who does not know the inert key exists reaches for a relation token and records a supersession that never happened. `awf check` validates the ref, requires the back-pointer on a target of any status **for every relation including a citation**, and refuses a token into a `Proposed` target.
- `{{ .layout.activeMd }}` continues to list both ADRs as live; the overridden anchors render in its "Superseded anchors on live ADRs" subsection, derived from the tokens and the `related:` linkage on **both** ADRs.
- Authoring-time rule: a new token targets the ADR that **currently owns** the anchor. A token whose target was later fully superseded degrades to an `awf check` advisory note, preserving history.
- Retirement: a `supersedes-invariant:` token carried by an **Implemented** ADR retires the slug from owed invariant backing. Because full supersedence now requires every declared slug to be retired explicitly, flipping a token-carrier to `Superseded` no longer silently lapses its retirements.

The back-pointer is owed when the successor overrides a **live** (`Accepted`/`Implemented`) predecessor's **Decision item or Invariant**. It is not owed for a citation that does not override, for an amendment of a `Proposed` ADR (edit that ADR in place instead), or for an edit that changes wording without changing meaning.
<!-- awf:end -->

## Procedure

Pick the status transition, then:

<!-- awf:section procedure-status-edit -->
1. **Edit the ADR's frontmatter `status` field** in place. On a live ADR only `status` and cross-reference metadata (`related:`) may be edited in place; the body remains append-only once the ADR leaves `Proposed`.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section procedure-predecessor-flip -->
2. **If this flip completes a predecessor's coverage:** update that predecessor's `status` field to bare `Superseded` in the **same commit**. Run `awf check` to find out - it names any ADR whose anchors are all retired but whose status has not caught up, and equally any `Superseded` ADR with an anchor still uncovered. Partial supersedence preserves the predecessor's status.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section state-doc-update -->
3. **Update any domain doc** under `{{ .layout.domainsDir }}` whose domain this ADR materially shifts: refresh the Current state prose if the domain's position has moved. The `## Decisions` index is generated from each ADR's `domains:` field; set that field, and do not hand-maintain a decisions table. Include any prose change in the same commit.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section procedure-regen -->
4. **Regenerate ACTIVE.md.** Run `{{ with .vars.activeMdRegenCmd }}{{ . }}{{ else }}awf sync{{ end }}` to regenerate `{{ .layout.activeMd }}`. Stage the result. Do not hand-edit `ACTIVE.md`; always regenerate and commit it alongside any ADR status change.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section procedure-gate -->
5. **Run the gate{{ with .vars.gateCmd }} (`{{ . }}`){{ end }}.** The gate's drift test validates that `ACTIVE.md` is in sync with the current ADR frontmatter. If it fails, regenerate and re-stage `ACTIVE.md` before retrying.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section commit-templates -->
## Commit subject templates

Use these subjects for each transition type:

- `docs(adr): accept NNNN <short title>` for `Proposed → Accepted`
- `<feat|fix|refactor>(<scope>): <subject> (implements NNNN)` for `Accepted → Implemented` in the final implementation commit
- `docs(adr): supersede NNNN with MMMM <short title>` in the successor's introducing commit; predecessor flip lands here
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section amendment-while-proposed -->
## Amendment-while-Proposed

While `status: Proposed`, all sections may be amended freely as edge cases or scope refinements surface. Two flavours:

- **Plain amendment.** Edit the relevant section; commit with `docs(adr): amend Context for <title>` or fold into a co-located implementation commit when the change is small.
- **Deferral.** When scope shrinks mid-flight, amend the still-`Proposed` ADR's Context with what was deferred and why; commit as `docs(adr): amend NNNN, defer <part>; <reason>`. Deferral is a Context edit on a `Proposed` ADR, not a lifecycle state; deferred work lands in a follow-up ADR or the roadmap.

Once `Accepted` or `Implemented`, the body's meaning is frozen; a schema retrofit may migrate its machine-readable encoding. Only the `status` field and cross-reference metadata (`related:`) are editable in place.
<!-- awf:end -->

## Notes

<!-- awf:section notes -->
- **Authoritative source:** `{{ .layout.workflowRef }}` and `{{ .layout.adrDir }}/README.md`. This skill is a procedural pointer, not a contract restatement.
- **Append-only rule:** once any live state is reached, only the `status` field and cross-reference metadata (`related:`) are editable in place. The body is the historical record: its meaning is frozen, and append-only protects rationale, not bookkeeping - a meaning-preserving schema retrofit may migrate its machine-readable encoding.
- **`{{ .layout.activeMd }}` is auto-generated** by `{{ with .vars.activeMdRegenCmd }}{{ . }}{{ else }}awf sync{{ end }}` and is **never hand-edited**. Always regenerate and commit it alongside any ADR status change.
- Does not commit on your behalf; surfaces the right edits for you to land.
<!-- awf:end -->
